of tourism. It particularly focuses on the 'power' of different forms of 'Otherness' to seduce and to disrupt, and, eventually, also to renew the social and cosmological orders of 'modern' culture and everyday life. Drawing on a series of ethnographic case studies, the contributors investigate the production, socialisation and symbolic encompassment of different 'Others' as a political and also an economic resource to govern social life in the present. The volume provides a comparative inductive study on the modernist philosophical concepts of time, 'Otherness', and the self in practice, and relates it to contemporary tourism and mobility.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCulture and tourism. 0aDifference (Psychology) 0aDifference (Psychology). 0aOther (Philosophy) 0aOther (Philosophy). 0aTourismxPsychological aspects. 4aSocial & cultural anthropology. 4aTourism industry. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Industries / Hospitality, Travel & Tourism.2bisacsh  aSelf-Other relations.  aexperience.  aidentity.  amodern culture.  aseduction.  atourism.  atourist behaviour.1 aDi Giovine, Michael A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDi Giovine, Michael A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGhasarian, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGupta, Pamila, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnapp, Marcela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMota Santos, Paula, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMármol, Camila del, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPicard, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPicard, David, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.go